@node "CanDo_Layout_Editor" "CanDo's Layout EditorTool"
@toc "CanDo_Main"
   With this EditorTool, you can integrate text into your CanDo
displays more easily than ever before. This tool allows you to flow
text, which you can load from a file or type in yourself, around
imagery or other display elements. You simply use the mouse to
guide the boundaries of the text layout area, and the script to
exactly reproduce your layout will be written for you. You may also
specify the font and style in which you want the text rendered.

   After starting up the Layout EditorTool it will open a window
and draw the default text flow area on your window. Whatever text
you layout will be flowed into this area.

   The Layout window has a simple text editor into which you can
type text, or load a text file. This tool has two menus:
   @{" Text   " link "CDR_Layout_Textmenu"}  @{" Margin " link "CDR_Layout_Marginmenu"}

Buttons...
   @{" Left    Top    Right " link "CDR_Layout_SetMargins"}
   @{" Set Font & Style     " link "CDR_Layout_SetFont"}
   @{" Preview the text     " link "CDR_Layout_Preview"}

   When you have set up your text flow area, and the text to go in
it, just the way you want it to be, press the @{fg highlight}OK@{fg text} button, and
Layout will type all the CanDo scripting commands necessary to
display your text within the text flow area. If you have a large
amount of text, this can produce a very large script.

   It is a good idea to save your text before pressing OK, if the
contents of the Layout editor are not already saved. The Layout
EditorTool cannot work backward from the script to calculate what
your text is or what the shape of the flow area is.

Embedded style and color changes...

   Embedded commands may be placed as part of the text that is to
be laid out. They have the effect of changing the colors and style
of the text which follows them.

   The commands, surrounded by the "Ģ" and "ģ" characters, are
entered into the text to be printed. To type the "Ģ" character,
hold down the ALT key and press 9. To type the "ģ" character, hold
down the ALT and press 0.

   @{" ĢPen...ģ       " link "CDR_Layout_EmbedPen"}
   @{" ĢDrawMode...ģ  " link "CDR_Layout_EmbedDrawMode"}
   @{" ĢStyle...ģ     " link "CDR_Layout_EmbedStyle"}
   
@endnode

@node "CDR_Layout_TextMenu" "CanDo's Layout EditorTool Text menu"
@toc "CanDo_Layout_Editor"
@{fg highlight}Load...@{fg text}

   This menu item will open the CanDo file requester and allow you
   to specify a text file to load into the Layout editor. After
   loading the text, you may type changes into it. Layout uses the
   text that is in the editor when it flows the text onto your
   display. It does not need the disk file after it has been loaded
   into the editor.
   
@{fg highlight}Save...@{fg text}

   This lets you save whatever text is in the Layout editor to a
   text file of your choosing
   
@{fg highlight}Insert...@{fg text}

   This item will add the contents of whatever text file you
   specify to the text already in the Layout editor.

@endnode

@node "CDR_Layout_MarginMenu" "CanDo's Layout EditorTool Margin menu"
@toc "CanDo_Layout_Editor"
@{fg highlight}Load...@{fg text}

   This will load a margin file from disk.
   
@{fg highlight}Save...@{fg text}

   This saves the current text flow area margins as a file. This
   can then be loaded back in at a later time.
   
@{fg highlight}Default...@{fg text}

   This will reset the margins back to the factory default locations.
   
@endnode

@node "CDR_Layout_Preview" "CanDo's Layout EditorTool Preview mode"
@toc "CanDo_Layout_Editor"
   At any time, you can see what the text will look like once it has
been flowed by pressing the button labeled @{fg highlight}Preview the text@{fg text} at
the right side of the display.

   When you press this button, a requester will open which tells you
how to stop previewing the text and return to the Layout EditorTool
control window. Pay careful attention to this information. To
return to the Layout control window you will have to press the
@{fg highlight}Escape@{fg text} key. After you press the @{fg highlight}OK@{fg text} button on this requester, Layout
will start to calculate the best way to flow you text. It will use
an hour-glass pointer to show you how it is progressing. After a
few seconds, your text will appear in the flow area on your window.

@endnode

@node "CDR_Layout_SetMargins" "CanDo's Layout EditorTool Margins"
@toc "CanDo_Layout_Editor"
   By using one of these three options, you can modify the
boundaries of the flow area, directly on you display. After
choosing one of the buttons, the Layout control window will move
out of your way and the pointer will turn into an arrow showing you
which side of the boundaries that you are editing. You can switch
between the three directions by using the arrow keys on you
keyboard. Pressing the up arrow, for example, will change your
pointer to an up arrow and you will then be in the mode to modify
the top boundary of the text flow, shape, area. To return to the
Layout control window just press the @{fg highlight}Escape@{fg text} key.

@{fg highlight}Left@{fg text}

   This mode allows you to change the left-hand boundary of the
   text flow area. Notice the left and right boundaries are made up
   of vertical slashes. By clicking on the display and dragging
   your mouse while in left arrow mode, you will move the
   individual slashes on the left-hand side of the text flow area.
   You may have to drag the mouse slowly to move each and every
   slash to the correct position. If you hold down the @{fg highlight}Shift@{fg text} key
   when you click the mouse button, the current slash you are over
   and all the ones below it move the mouse's current position.

@{fg highlight}Top@{fg text}

   This allows you to set the top boundary for the text flow area.
   Just click in your window and drag the mouse. The horizontal
   line represents the top boundary. Release the mouse button when
   you have the boundary at the proper location.

@{fg highlight}Right@{fg text}

   This lets you adjust the right-hand boundary of the text flow
   area in the same manner as the left.

@endnode

@node "CDR_Layout_SetFont" "CanDo's Layout EditorTool SetFont"
@toc "CanDo_Layout_Editor"
   You can also control the initial font and text style of the
flowed text by pressing the button labeled @{fg highlight}Set Font & Style@{fg text}. This
will open the CanDo Font/Text requester from which you can specify
the font and point size to use, as well as the style, including
CanDo's special extended text styles.

   After setting the font and style, Layout will recalculate the
the text flow area. This may take a few seconds.

@endnode

@node "CDR_Layout_EmbedPen" "CanDo's Layout EditorTool Embedded Pen change"
@toc "CanDo_Layout_Editor"
@{fg highlight}ĢPen a[,b]ģ@{fg text}

   This changes the value of PenA, and optionally PenB, which are
used to display the text. This command is typed directly with the
text to be displayed. This embedded command will actually generate
the @{" SetPen " link "CanDo_SetPen"} command. For example, the following text may be
typed into the document of the Layout Editor Tool:


@{fg highlight}Example:@{fg text}
   The letter ĢPen 2ģ Z ĢPen 1,0ģ is a different color.

   The letter "Z" will be drawn using color register 2, while the
rest of the letters would be in color 1. The default colors are
ĢPen 1,0ģ and may be changed with this command, or through the
option in the EditorTool. The second number, or PenB, is used when
in draw mode Jam2.

@endnode

@node "CDR_Layout_EmbedDrawMode" "CanDo's Layout EditorTool Embedded DrawMode change"
@toc "CanDo_Layout_Editor"
@{fg highlight}ĢDrawMode Normal|Jam1|Jam2|Complement|Inverseģ@{fg text}

   This changes the manner in which text is drawn to the screen.
The draw mode options are the same as described for the
@{" SetDrawMode " link "CanDo_SetDrawMode"} command.

There are five additional variations of this command:
   @{fg highlight}ĢNormalģ@{fg text}
   @{fg highlight}ĢJam1ģ@{fg text}
   @{fg highlight}ĢJam2ģ@{fg text}
   @{fg highlight}ĢComplementģ@{fg text}
   @{fg highlight}ĢInverseģ@{fg text}

@{fg highlight}Example:@{fg text}
   Hello Ģdrawmode inverseģoutĢdrawmode normalģ in TV land.
   Hello ĢinverseģoutĢnormalģ in TV land, again.
@endnode

@node "CDR_Layout_EmbedStyle" "CanDo's Layout EditorTool Embedded Style change"
@toc "CanDo_Layout_Editor"
@{fg highlight}ĢStyle Plain|Bold|Underline|Italicģ@{fg text}

   This changes the style of the text being displayed. These
options are the same as described for the @{" SetPrintStyle " link "CanDo_SetPrintStyle"}
command.

There are four additional variations of this command:
   @{fg highlight}ĢPlainģ@{fg text}
   @{fg highlight}ĢBoldģ@{fg text}
   @{fg highlight}ĢUnderlineģ@{fg text}
   @{fg highlight}ĢItalicģ@{fg text}

@{fg highlight}Example:@{fg text}
   Hello Ģstyle underlineģoutĢstyle plainģ in TV land.
   Hello ĢunderlineģoutĢplainģ in TV land, again.
@endnode

